--- title: "Cálculo numérico y simbólico con Julia" subtitle: "Seminario de Innovación Docente
Universidade da Coruña" author: "Alfredo Sánchez Alberca   [{{< fa envelope >}}](mailto:asalber@ceu.es) [{{< fa brands twitter >}}](https://twitter.com/aprendeconalf) [{{< fa home >}}](https://aprendeconalf.es)" date: 07-21-2023 date-format: long title-slide-attributes: #data-background-color: black data-background-image: img/prompt-julia.png data-background-size: contain lang: es fig-align: center --- # ¿Qué es Julia? [Julia](https://julialang.org/) un lenguaje de programación moderno creado en 2012 el MIT por el equipo del profesor Edelman, orientado a cálculo científico y el análisis de datos. De los creadores de Julia: >_We want a language that is:_ > - _Open source._ - _With the speed of C._ - _Obvious, familiar mathematical notation like Matlab._ - _As usable for general programming as Python._ - _As easy for statistics as R._ - _As natural for string processing as Perl._ - _As powerful for linear algebra as Matlab._ - _As good at gluing programs together as the shell._ - _Dirt simple to learn, yet keeps the most serious hackers happy._ # Experiencia docente Prácticas en el Grado de Ingeniería Matemática :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="32%"} Curso 2022/2023 - Álgebra Lineal - Análisis I y II - Matemática Discreta ::: ::: {.column width="32%"} Curso 2023/2024 - Análisis III - Ecuaciones Diferenciales - Ecuaciones en Derivadas Parciales - Geometría Diferencial - Métodos numéricos I y II ::: ::: {.column width="32%"} Curso 2024/2025 - Aprendizaje automático - Redes neuronales - Series temporales - Procesamiento del lenguaje natural ::: :::: # ¿Por qué Julia? ## Sencillez Lenguaje de alto nivel con una sintaxis fácil de aprender (similar a Python, R o Matlab). ::: {.cell execution_count=2} ``` {.julia .cell-code} println("¡Hola Julia!") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` ¡Hola Julia! ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=3} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] n = length(x) media = sum(x) / n varianza = sum(x.^2) / n - media^2 (media, varianza) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=3} ``` (3.0, 2.0) ``` ::: ::: ## Rapidez Julia es un lenguaje muy veloz (equiparable a C o Fortran en muchas tareas). ![Comparativa de Julia con otros lenguajes](img/benchmarks.svg) --- ### Cálculo de pi por el método de Leibniz :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="32%"} Julia ```julia function pi(n) pi = 0.0; op = 1 for i in 0:n pi += op*4/(2i+1) op *= -1 end return pi end pi(10^9) ``` $\approx$ 1 seg ::: ::: {.column width="32%"} C ```c double pi(double n) { double pi = 0; int i = 0; int op = 1; for (i; i < n; i++) { pi += op*4/(2*i+1); op *= -1; } return pi; } int main() { pi(1000000000); } ``` $\approx$ 3 seg ::: ::: {.column width="35%"} Python ```python def pi(n): pi = 0; op = 1 for i in range(n): pi += op*4/(2*i+1) op *= -1 return pi pi(10^9) ``` $\approx$ 78 seg ::: :::: --- ### Despacho múltiple La razón por la que Julia es tan rápido es por que usa [_despacho múltiple_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_dispatch) para precompilar distintas versiones de una misma función para cada posible tipo de dato de sus argumentos. ## Tipos de datos numéricos ![](img/tipos-datos-numericos.png) --- :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="45%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=4} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=4} ``` Int64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=5} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(Int16(1)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=5} ``` Int16 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=6} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1.0) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=6} ``` Float64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=7} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1.0f0) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=7} ``` Float32 ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="45%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=8} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1//2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=8} ``` Rational{Int64} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=9} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(pi) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=9} ``` Irrational{:π} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=10} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1+1im) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=10} ``` Complex{Int64} ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: --- ### Enteros | Tipo | Signo | Bits | Min | Max | |:-|:-:|-:|-:|-:| | Int8 | ✓ | 8 | $-2^7$ | $2^7-1$ | | UInt8 | | 8 | $0$ | $2^8-1$ | | Int16 | ✓ | 16 | $-2^{15}$ | $2^{15}-1$ | | UInt16 | | 16 | $0$ | $2^{16}-1$ | | Int32 | ✓ | 32 | $-2^{31}$ | $2^{31}-1$ | | UInt32 | | 32 | $0$ | $2^{32}-1$ | | Int64 | ✓ | 64 | $-2^{63}$ | $2^{63}-1$ | | UInt64 | | 64 | $0$ | $2^{64}-1$ | | Int128 | ✓ | 128 | $-2^{127}$ | $2^{127}-1$ | | UInt128 | | 128 | $0$ | $2^{128}-1$ | | Bool | N/A | 8 | false (0) | true (1) | --- ### Reales en coma flotante | Tipo | Bits | Min | Max | |:-|-:|-:|-:|-:|-:| | Float16 | 16 | $-6.55e4$ | $6.55e4$ | | Float32 | 32 | $-3.4028235e38$ | $3.4028235e38$ | | Float64 | 64 | $-1.7976931348623157e308$ | $1.7976931348623157e308$ | | Tipo | Min positive | Epsilon | |:-|-:|-:| | Float16 | $6.104e-5$ | $0.000977$ | | Float32 | $1.1754944f-38$ | $1.1920929f-7$ | | Float64 | $2.2250738585072014e-308$ | $2.220446049250313e-16$ | --- ## Precisión arbitraria - `BigInt` permite representar enteros de cualquier tamaño. - `BigFloat` permite representar reales de cualquier tamaño y precisión. El límite lo marca la memoria del ordenador. ::: {.cell execution_count=11} ``` {.julia .cell-code} BigFloat(pi) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=11} ``` 3.141592653589793238462643383279502884197169399375105820974944592307816406286198 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=12} ``` {.julia .cell-code} BigFloat(pi, precision = 1000) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=12} ``` 3. ``` ::: ::: --- ### Definición de nuevos tipos ::: {.cell execution_count=13} ``` {.julia .cell-code} struct EvenInt <: Integer num :: Signed # inner constructor function EvenInt(num) @assert iseven(num) new(num) end end EvenInt(4) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=13} ``` EvenInt(4) ``` ::: ::: --- ### Aritmética racional :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="45%"} - Simplifiación ::: {.cell execution_count=14} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 4 // 6 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=14} ``` 2//3 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=15} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 4 // 6 == 2 // 3 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=15} ``` true ``` ::: ::: - Suma y resta ::: {.cell execution_count=16} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 1 // 6 + 2 // 4 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=16} ``` 2//3 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=17} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 2 // 3 - 1 // 6 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=17} ``` 1//2 ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="45%"} - Producto ::: {.cell execution_count=18} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 2 // 3 * 3 // 4 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=18} ``` 1//2 ``` ::: ::: - Cociente ::: {.cell execution_count=19} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 3 // 4 / 2 // 3 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=19} ``` 9//8 ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: --- ### Aritmética compleja La constante `im` está asociada al número complejo $i=\sqrt{-1}$. :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="45%"} - Suma y resta ::: {.cell execution_count=20} ``` {.julia .cell-code} (1 + 2im) + (1 - im) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=20} ``` 2 + 1im ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=21} ``` {.julia .cell-code} (1 + 2im) - (1 + im) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=21} ``` 0 + 1im ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="45%"} - Producto ::: {.cell execution_count=22} ``` {.julia .cell-code} (1 + 2im) * (2 - 3im) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=22} ``` 8 + 1im ``` ::: ::: - Cociente ::: {.cell execution_count=23} ``` {.julia .cell-code} (1 + 2im) / (1 - 2im) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=23} ``` -0.6 + 0.8im ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: --- ### Promoción de tipos Siempre se promociona hacia el tipo más general. ::: {.column width="45%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=24} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(Int16(1) + 2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=24} ``` Int64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=25} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1.0 + 2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=25} ``` Float64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=26} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1 / 2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=26} ``` Float64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=27} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1 // 2 + 0.5) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=27} ``` Float64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=28} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(sqrt(1 // 2)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=28} ``` Float64 ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="45%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=29} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof((1 // 2) ^ 2.0) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=29} ``` Float64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=30} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(1.0 + 2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=30} ``` Float64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=31} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(2(1+0im)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=31} ``` Complex{Int64} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=32} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(im^2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=32} ``` Complex{Int64} ``` ::: ::: :::: --- ## Tipos de datos compuestos ::::{.columns} :::{.column width="55%"} - Vectores ::: {.cell execution_count=33} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof([1, 2, 3]) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=33} ::: {.ansi-escaped-output} ```{=html} 
Vector{Int64} (alias for Array{Int64, 1})
``` ::: ::: ::: - Matrices ::: {.cell execution_count=34} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof([1 2 3; 4 5 6]) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=34} ::: {.ansi-escaped-output} ```{=html} 
Matrix{Int64} (alias for Array{Int64, 2})
``` ::: ::: ::: - Tuplas ::: {.cell execution_count=35} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof((1, "enero", 2020)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=35} ``` Tuple{Int64, String, Int64} ``` ::: ::: ::: :::{.column width="41%"} - Diccionarios ::: {.cell execution_count=36} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(Dict("x" => 1, "y" => 2)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=36} ``` Dict{String, Int64} ``` ::: ::: - Conjuntos ::: {.cell execution_count=37} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(Set([2, 4, 6])) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=37} ``` Set{Int64} ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: Los tipos compuestos incluyen parámetros que determinan el tipo de sus elementos. --- ### Álgebra de conjuntos ::::{.columns} :::{.column width="48%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=38} ``` {.julia .cell-code} A = Set([2, 4]) B = Set([1, 2, 3]) 3 ∈ A ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=38} ``` false ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=39} ``` {.julia .cell-code} A ⊆ B ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=39} ``` false ``` ::: ::: ::: :::{.column width="48%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=40} ``` {.julia .cell-code} A ∪ B ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=40} ``` Set{Int64} with 4 elements: 4 2 3 1 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=41} ``` {.julia .cell-code} A ∩ B ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=41} ``` Set{Int64} with 1 element: 2 ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: Es fácil definir nuevos operadores. ::: {.cell execution_count=42} ``` {.julia .cell-code} const \ˢ = setdiff A \ˢ B ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=42} ``` Set{Int64} with 1 element: 4 ``` ::: ::: --- ### Aritmética infinita e indeterminaciones :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="45%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=43} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 1 / Inf ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=43} ``` 0.0 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=44} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 1 / 0 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=44} ``` Inf ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=45} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 0 / 0 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=45} ``` NaN ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=46} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Inf + 1 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=46} ``` Inf ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=47} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 1 - Inf ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=47} ``` -Inf ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="45%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=48} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Inf + Inf ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=48} ``` Inf ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=49} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Inf - Inf ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=49} ``` NaN ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=50} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Inf / Inf ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=50} ``` NaN ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=51} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 0 / 0 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=51} ``` NaN ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=52} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 0 * Inf ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=52} ``` NaN ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: ## Definición de funciones Julia admite múltiples formas de definir funciones. - Tradicional. Similar a otros lenguajes de programación. ```julia function area_triángulo(base, altura) base * altura / 2 end ``` - En línea. Muy cómoda para definir funciones matemáticas. ```julia area_triángulo(base, altura) = base * altura / 2 ``` - Funciones anónimas. Se utilizan sobre todo en programación funcional, como argumentos de otras funciones. ```julia area_triángulo = (base, altura) -> base * altura / 2 ``` ## Programación funcional Las funciones son objetos que pueden asignarse o pasarse como argumentos de otras funciones. ::: {.cell execution_count=53} ``` {.julia .cell-code} square(x) = x * x cuadrado = square cuadrado(2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=53} ``` 4 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=54} ``` {.julia .cell-code} componer(f, g) = f ∘ g componer(log, sin)(pi/2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=54} ``` 0.0 ``` ::: ::: --- ### Vectorización de funciones y operadores El operador punto `.` permite aplicar una función u operador a los elementos de una colección (arrays, vectores, tuplas, etc.) ::: {.cell execution_count=55} ``` {.julia .cell-code} v = [1, 2, 3] cuadrado.(v) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=55} ``` 3-element Vector{Int64}: 1 4 9 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=56} ``` {.julia .cell-code} w = [0, 1, 2] v .^ w ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=56} ``` 3-element Vector{Int64}: 1 2 9 ``` ::: ::: ## Expresividad matemática ### Acepta Unicode Julia permite caracteres [Unicode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Unicode_characters) lo que facilita la expresión de fórmulas matemáticas. Para ello se utilizan [códigos especiales](https://docs.julialang.org/en/v1/manual/unicode-input/) (en muchos casos son los mismos que en $\LaTeX$), pulsando después la tecla de tabulación. ::: {.cell execution_count=57} ``` {.julia .cell-code} # Introducir \alpha + TAB α = 1 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=57} ``` 1 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=58} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 😄 = "julia" 😄 ^ 2 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=58} ``` "juliajulia" ``` ::: ::: --- ### Composición de funciones El operador `∘` permite componer funciones. ::: {.cell execution_count=59} ``` {.julia .cell-code} f(x) = sin(x) g(x) = log(x) (g ∘ f)(pi/2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=59} ``` 0.0 ``` ::: ::: También puede realizarse con el operador de tubería `|>` (similar a %>% en R). ::: {.cell execution_count=60} ``` {.julia .cell-code} pi / 2 |> sin |> log ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=60} ``` 0.0 ``` ::: ::: --- ### Integración con $\LaTeX$ El paquete `Latexify` permite obtener el código $\LaTeX$ para representar cualquier expresión matemática. ::: {.cell execution_count=61} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Latexify expr = :((x-y)/(x+y)^2) latexify(expr) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=61} $\frac{x - y}{\left( x + y \right)^{2}}$ ::: ::: ## Integración con Quarto [Quarto](https://quarto.org/) es un sistema de publicación de textos científicos y técnicos de alta calidad basado en Markdown y $\LaTeX$ (similar a RMarkdown). Julia es uno de los lenguajes de programación que admite. ## Orientación al cálculo numérico Lenguaje de propósito general, pero especialmente diseñado para el cálculo científico y el análisis de datos. # Aplicaciones Matemáticas ## Representación gráfica de funciones El paquete `Plots` permite la representación gráfica de funciones con diversos tipos de diagramas. ::::{.columns} ::: {.column width="48%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=62} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Plots plot(sin, 0, 2pi, label = "sen", size = (480,400)) plot!(cos, label = "cos") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=62} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="48%"} ::: {.cell execution_count=63} ``` {.julia .cell-code} xs = ys = range(-3,3, length=100) f(x,y) = 2sin(x^2+y^2) / (x^2+y^2) surface(xs, ys, f, size = (480, 400)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=63} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: --- ::: {.cell execution_count=64} ``` {.julia .cell-code} plotlyjs() xs = ys = range(-3,3, length=100) f(x,y) = 2sin(x^2+y^2) / (x^2+y^2) surface(xs, ys, f) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html}

``` ::: ::: ## Cálculo simbólico Existen dos paquetes para cálculo simbólico: - `SymPy`: Basado en el paquete `sympy` de Phthon. Muy maduro, pero lento. - `Symbolics`. Paquete puro en Julia muy rápido, pero no tan completo. --- ### Declaración de variables (símbolos) ::::{.columns} :::{.column width="48%"} SymPy ::: {.cell execution_count=65} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using SymPy @syms x::real y::real typeof(x) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=65} ``` Sym ``` ::: ::: ::: :::{.column width="48%"} Symbolics ::: {.cell execution_count=66} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Symbolics @variables x y; typeof(x) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=66} ``` Num ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: --- ### Simplificación ::::{.columns} :::{.column width="48%"} SymPy ::: {.cell execution_count=67} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using SymPy @syms x::real SymPy.simplify(sin(x)^2 + cos(x)^2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=67} $1$ ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=68} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using SymPy @syms x::real SymPy.expand((x + 1)^2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=68} $x^{2} + 2 x + 1$ ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=69} ``` {.julia .cell-code} SymPy.factor(x^3 - x^2 + x - 1) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=69} $\left(x - 1\right) \left(x^{2} + 1\right)$ ::: ::: ::: :::{.column width="48%"} Symbolics ::: {.cell execution_count=70} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Symbolics @variables x; Symbolics.simplify(sin(x)^2 + cos(x)^2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=70} $$ \begin{equation} 1 \end{equation} $$ ::: ::: ::: :::: --- ### Sustitución de variables ::::{.columns} :::{.column width="48%"} SymPy ::: {.cell execution_count=71} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using SymPy @syms x y expr = cos(x*y) expr.subs([(x, 2), (y, π)]) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=71} $1.0$ ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=72} ``` {.julia .cell-code} expr(x=>2, y=>π) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=72} $1$ ::: ::: ::: :::{.column width="48%"} Symbolics ::: {.cell execution_count=73} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Symbolics @variables x y expr = cos(x*y) substitute(expr, Dict([x=>2, y=>π])) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=73} $$ ``` ::: ::: # Inconvenientes ## Demora en la primera ejecución Al precompilar cualquier función la primera ejecución se demora un poco. Esta demora puede ser significativa en paquetes que incorporan muchas funciones (por ejemplo Plots). Se puede evitar con el paquete [`JuliaInterpreter`](https://juliadebug.github.io/JuliaInterpreter.jl/stable/). ## Control del desbordamiento Cuando se excede el mayor valor que puede representarse con un tipo, no se produce un error de desbordamiento, sino que se aplica aritmética modular y se continúa contando a partir del mínimo. ::: {.cell execution_count=120} ``` {.julia .cell-code} 10^19 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=120} ``` -8446744073709551616 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=121} ``` {.julia .cell-code} BigInt(10)^19 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=121} ``` 10000000000000000000 ``` ::: ::: ## Redefinición de variables como constantes y viceversa Aunque Julia es un lenguaje de tipado dinámico como Python, no permite redefinir una constante como una variable o viceversa. Hay que tener en cuenta que las funciones se definen como constantes por lo que no se puede utilizar el mismo nombre para una variable y una función. ```julia x = 1 const x = 2 ``` ```sh ERROR: cannot declare x constant; it already has a value Stacktrace: [1] top-level scope @ REPL[1]:1 ``` ```julia f = 1 f(x) = 2x ``` ```sh ERROR: cannot define function f; it already has a value Stacktrace: [1] top-level scope @ none:0 [2] top-level scope @ REPL[3]:1 ``` ## Mezcla de sintaxis de otros lenguajes - Las comillas simples se usan para representar caracteres y las dobles para cadenas. - El operador de exponenciación es `^` (y no `**` como en Python). - Los operadores lógicos `&` (conjunción), `|` (disyunción) y `!` (negación), (y no `and`, `or` y `not` como en Python). - Operador de concatenación de cadenas `*` (y no `+` como en Python). - El indexado de arrays comienza en 1 (y no en 0 como en Python). - Los rangos para la indexación tienen sintaxis `inicio:salto:fin` (y no `inicio:(fin+1):salto` como en Python). - El operador de resto de la división entera es `%` (y no el módulo como en Python). - La unidad imaginaria $\sqrt{-1}$ se representa `im` (y no `j` como en Python). # Paquetes para Matemáticas ## Cálculo simbólico -
